      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and im kinda confused. i feel like i'm paying a lot every month but the actual amount i owe isnt going down as much as i thought it would. can u explain how the interest actually works with the payments? why does it seem like so much of my money is just disappearing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I can help explain that. When you make a payment on your student loan, a portion of it goes towards the principal amount you owe, and the rest goes towards interest. The interest is calculated on the remaining balance of your loan, so if you only make minimum payments, a lot of your payment goes towards interest rather than reducing the principal. It's like paying the interest on a growing pile of coins in a jar. The more you pay towards the principal, the faster you'll see your balance decrease. It's a bit like trying to empty a jar with just a spoon – it takes time and effort to make significant progress.",
